{"id":"1602.09014","submitter":"Michel Boer","authors":"O. Bardho, B. Gendre, A. Rossi, L. Amati, J. Haislip, A. Klotz, E.\n  Palazzi, D. Reichart, A.S. Trotter, M. Boer","title":"GRB 141221A: gone is the wind","comments":"9 pages, 5 figures, 7 tables, accepted for publication in MNRAS","journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1093/mnras/stw537","report-no":null,"categories":"astro-ph.HE","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  GRB 141221A was observed from infrared to soft gamma-ray bands. Here, we\ninvestigate its properties, in light of the standard model. We find that the\noptical light curve of the afterglow of this burst presents an unusual\nsteep/quick rise. The broad band spectral energy distribution taken near the\nmaximum of the optical emission presents either a thermal component or a\nspectral break. In the former case, the properties of the afterglow are then\nvery unusual, but could explain the lack of apparent jet breaks in the Swift\nlight curves. In the latter case, the afterglow properties of this burst are\nmore usual, and we can see in the light curves the passing through of the\ninjection and cooling frequencies within the optical bands, not masked by a\nreverse shock. This model also excludes the presence of a stellar wind,\nchallenging either the stellar progenitor properties, or the very stellar\nnature of the progenitor itself. In all cases, this burst may be a part of a\nRosetta stone that could help to explain some of the most striking features\ndiscovered by Swift during the last ten years.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 29 Feb 2016 15:54:41 GMT"}],"update_date":"2016-03-23"}
